\begin{abstract}
Energy efficiency is increasingly regarded as a requirement in the implementation of algorithms. Understanding better how energy is spent in a system is a prerequisite from which methodologies that effectively compare different configurations and provide actionable insights to software developers can be built. In this paper, we will investigate how the system operating environment, specifically temperature and CPU core choice, along with system measures for keeping temperature in check, influence energy measurements in a population-based optimization algorithm, establish a model of this influence and, from this understanding, create a system that makes the influence of algorithm parameters on energy spent clearer, while, if possible, minimizing energy spent in the experiment runs. We find that, in a two-die system, accounting for silicon die temperatures during launch processes enables us to achieve this goal.
\end{abstract}

