\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Green computing, Energy profiling
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction and state of the art}

The focus in software engineering has lately shifted from optimizing for performance toward {\em greening} algorithm implementations, an area that needs reliable methodologies and models; two critical areas, but fraught with technical challenges. The primary obstacle is that, unlike traditional performance metrics, it is impossible to isolate the energy consumption of a single process running on a specific core under any modern operating system (OS), simply due to the lack of per-core sensors that are able to take those measurements. The best effort is to synchronize energy measurements with process execution and subsequently attempt to isolate the system overhead. Subsequently, algorithm-specific energy consumption, independent of language and runtime framework, must then be additionally isolated. Standard practice involves taking baseline measurements to account for OS and framework overhead, then subtracting these from workload measurements to estimate the "real" energy consumed, but no matter what you do, you will still measure what the device is consuming {\em while your process is running in it}, not the extra power the specific core has required from the source or how much energy has spent while in it \cite{lion24}. That is, what you measure is $E(t,\omega) = E_i(t,\omega)+E_s(t,\omega)$. Measuring the energy spent by the system $E_s(t,\omega)$ by measuring idle system energy consumption or even considering $E_i(t,\omega) = E_w(t,\omega)+E_b(t,\omega)$, that is, splitting implementation energy in workload $E_w$ and baseline $E_b$ energy and measuring together $E_b(t,\omega)+E_w(t,\omega)$, the measured energy spent by the workload will still depend on the time and the operating conditions $\omega$. And operating conditions will change depending on external factors, as well as the influence of the workload; they will also affect the running time of each experiment.

Modern chipsets and OSs actively manage thermal envelopes through Dynamic Voltage and Frequency Scaling (DVFS) and Dynamic Power Management (DPM) \cite{snowdon2005power}; additionally, some modern processors have heterogeneous cores dividing them between high-performance "P" or "Performance" cores and energy-efficient "E" cores. The OS will assign a new process to a core with different voltage and frequency depending on unpredictable conditions. For scientists working on non-dedicated personal computers running other software besides the algorithm implementation that is the object of the measurement, the system state is in constant flux. Power reduction measures and thermal throttling are triggered not just by the workload under study, but by background processes and OS core election policies, which may move tasks between "performance" and "efficiency" cores unpredictably. This is why creating "warm-up" or "clean" conditions, or disabling frequency scaling, is not an option, because a real system will behave in a totally different way when your algorithm implementation is running alongside other software.

In modern Linux x86 based systems we can rely on several sensors in order to measure energy and the operating condition, besides the aforementioned time. Per-die temperature can be measured via system sensors; energy is measured via command-line utilities such as {\sf pinpoint} \cite{pinpoint} that rely on the RAPL power-and-energy measurement API \cite{rapl}. Core voltage and frequency cannot be measured directly; we will use running time as a proxy for these two quantities, since the effect of reducing voltage and frequency will increment running time. Using these sensors, the main research question we will answer if we can provide an energy measurement methodology and model that is able to maximize the influence of the workload under study and its parameters on energy consumption, minimizing the influence of the operating environment, so that comparisons between different configurations can be made meaningfully.

So far, research in this area has been significant; to mitigate these thermal and state-based biases, several experimental strategies have been proposed; for instance, implementing a cool-down phase after each measurement to allow thermal stabilization \cite{cotta25}. However, this remains difficult to guarantee in real-world environments where background processes are beyond the researcher's control. The "Robin and Rotate" (R3) approach \cite{rigorous} attempts to achieve reproducibility by running cycles of experimental variants in shifting orders. This design aims to mitigate changing system states and background consumption without requiring a system reboot between every run. Ultimately, while experimental design can mitigate some "noise", a gap remains in modeling how the operational context, specifically temperature and OS-level core election, directly biases the comparison of algorithm configurations. This creates a need for methodologies that do not just rotate experimental order, but explicitly account for the non-linear influence of thermal states on the resulting energy data.

\section{Experimental methodology and results}\label{sec:results}

Our workload in this paper is an implementation of the Brave New Algorithm \cite{merelo2022brave}. It is a stochastic, population-based optimization algorithm. All experiments are executed as single-threaded processes, which are then run on a single core of the processor at a time. The algorithm is configured to minimize the Sphere function across several parameter configurations, with
problem dimension ($D$) equal to 3, 5, or 10, population size ($N$): 200 or 400, and a termination criteria ($G$) equal to 10 or 25 generations without improvement. This last parameter is irrelevant to the measurements, but has been used in the experiments, which is why we list it here. Population size, however, could potentially have an influence on the energy consumption of the algorithm. The algorithm ends when an optimum is found, or when a series of iterations without any change occur. The energy spent by the implementation will depend on \begin{itemize}
\item The operating environment, represented by die temperature $T$ and, as indicated above, running time $R$.
\item Algorithm parameters: different problem dimensions $D$ and population size $P$
\item Algorithm outcomes: running time depends also on the algorithm, but the number of problem evaluations could potentially have an influence on the energy consumed
\end{itemize}

In order to be able to compute $E_w$, we make two kind of runs: $W$ runs run the whole algorithm to completion, $B$ (baseline) runs only create the initial population; these are run in a {\em sandwich} $B-W-B....W-B$ configuration, with 30 $W$ and 31 $B$, seeking to make operating conditions for them as close as possible. The energy consumption for any given workload $W_i$ is calculated by subtracting the average of the two surrounding baselines ($B_i$ and $B_{i+1}$) from the workload measurement. A whole experiment will run these processes for all parameter combination; then, it will be repeated 4 or 5 times, non-sequentially, at different moments in the day and after turning on the computer. This tries to ensure we gather data for as many different conditions as possible.

Measurements were conducted on a desktop system with an AMD Ryzen 9 9950X. This CPU features a 16 core, two-die architecture (called {\em chiplets}), allowing us to monitor temperature via two distinct sensors ({\tt Tccd1} and {\tt Tccd2}) using the {\tt k10temp-pci-00c3} driver. The interesting thing about this chip is that although architecturally it is homogeneous, during the process of fabrication cores are graded by their frequency capability and ranked according to it, giving those capable of higher frequencies the highest ID, and going down from there \footnote{Please consult the technical explanation in documents such as \url{https://www.reddit.com/r/Amd/comments/dzjs7i/fastest_cores_is_windows_right_or_ryzen_master/}.}.
The operating environment is Ubuntu (Kernel {\tt 6.17.0-14-generic}). We utilize {\sf pinpoint} to tap the RAPL API \cite{pinpoint}. On this AMD architecture, measurements are restricted to Package (PKG) energy. The BNA algorithm is implemented in the language Julia, which uses a JIT compiler. A Perl script (running in superuser mode) automates the execution, processes readings from the `sensors` command, and outputs a CSV file.
