<<icsme.base, echo=FALSE, fig.cap="Baseline energy consumption over running time, including average temperature", fig.height=4, fig.env="figure*">>=
load("data/joint_base_taskset_with_die2.rds")
library(ggplot2)
library(scales)
custom_pow <- trans_new(
  name = "custom_pow",
  transform = function(x) x^0.3,  # Lower power = more stretch at the bottom
  inverse = function(x) x^(1/0.3)
)
ggplot(joint_base_taskset_with_die2, aes(x=seconds,y=PKG, color=initial_temp)) +
  scale_color_viridis_c(trans=custom_pow) +
  geom_point() + theme_minimal() + labs(x="Time (s)", y="Energy Consumption (PKG)", color="Initial average temperature")
@

As a baseline, we have run a series of experiments, in three different batches: one using a {\em natural} assignment of process to dies, the other two restricting the process either to die 1 (which would have the $P$-cores) or 2 (with the $E$ cores). For the initial analysis we will consider the $B$ and $W$ runs different workloads: the energy consumption of the $B$ runs should have a minimal dependence on algorithm parameters or problem size. This is intended as an initial exploration of the statistical models with a workload with a very small dependence on the algorithm parameters. We chart energy consumed vs. time in Figure \ref{fig:icsme.base}.

<<icsme.model, echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap="Model of energy consumption as a function of time and temperature", fig.height=4, fig.pos="h!tb" >>=
initial_base_model <- glm(PKG ~ I(initial_temp_1^2)*I(initial_temp_2^2) + initial_temp_1*initial_temp_2*dimension*population_size+seconds, data=joint_base_taskset_with_die2)

base_time_model <- glm(seconds ~ dimension*population_size + initial_temp_1*initial_temp_2, data=joint_base_taskset_with_die2)
joint_base_taskset_with_die2$residual_seconds <- residuals(base_time_model)

initial_base_model_residualized <- glm(PKG ~ initial_temp_1*initial_temp_2*dimension*population_size+residual_seconds+I(initial_temp_1^2)*I(initial_temp_2^2) , data=joint_base_taskset_with_die2)
anova_initial_base_model_residualized <- anova(initial_base_model_residualized, test="F")

library(equatiomatic)
extract_eq(initial_base_model, wrap = TRUE,
           use_coefs = TRUE,
        raw_indices = TRUE,
        terms_per_line = 2,
        env="equation*",
        swap_var_names = c(
    "initial_temp_1"  = "T1",
    "I(initial_temp_2^2)" = "T2^2",
    "initial_temp_2"  = "T2",
    "I(initial_temp_1^2)" = "T1^2",
    "dimension"  = "D",
    "population_size" = "P",
    "residual_seconds" = "R"
  ), label="eq1" )

sum_F_anova_initial_base_model_residualized <- sum(anova_initial_base_model_residualized$F[2:nrow(anova_initial_base_model_residualized)])

variance_anova_initial <- 100*(anova_initial_base_model_residualized$F[2]+anova_initial_base_model_residualized$F[3]+anova_initial_base_model_residualized$F[6])/sum_F_anova_initial_base_model_residualized
variance_explained_system_percent <- round(variance_anova_initial, 2)
@

In order to understand the dependence of our measurement on the system operating conditions, we create a statistical model in two stages. The first stage models the running time $R$ using a generalized linear model {\sf glm} on the rest of the parameters; the residuals are then extracted, so that the $R$ parameter contains only non-explained variance. Then a second model that includes all parameters is created, again using {\sf glm}
This is shown in Equation \ref{eq: eq1}. Since there are so many samples, all terms are significant, including the algorithm parameters, but the interesting issue here is how much of the variance is explained by these. In fact, die temperatures and time explain
\Sexpr{variance_explained_system_percent}\%
of the variance. In this small workload, there is indeed little room for actual algorithm parameters.

Our stated objective is, as indicated, to find a way to constrain the dependence of our energy measurements on the operating conditions so that we can measure, with a higher precision, the consumption of two different configurations and present it in an actionable way. And this first model allows us to understand better how the operational context works; there are two negative terms on the square of temperatures: the system will be actively trying to turn down the amount of energy spent when the temperature is going up, and it will do so depending on the die: if the temperature of the second die goes up, it will more actively act to reduce it. This can be seen also on the positive dependence on the linear temperature term: the coefficient is bigger for $T_2$, the temperature of the second die: if it is higher, it is because more processes are running on it, and it will spend more energy because it takes longer. Time is always important: every second more will consume around 200 Joules (without taking into account other temperature terms, of course). We can already affirm that if the system temperature goes up, over all if it does in the second die, the system will act so that it eventually consumes less; however, the analysis of variance implies that in this admittedly very small workload algorithm parameters are two orders of magnitude less important than the operating context.

Although this model of the baseline runs might give us an initial idea of how temperature and power/frequency shape energy consumption, our interest is really in examining how much the workload actually spends.

<<icsme.baseline.workload, echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, fig.cap="Workload energy consumption for the baseline experiments", fig.height=3 >>=
load("data/europar_die1_workload.rds")
load("data/europar_taskset_die2_processed.rds")

initial_workload <- rbind( europar_die1_workload, europar_taskset_die2_processed )
ggplot(initial_workload, aes(x=delta_seconds,y=delta_PKG, color=initial_temp)) +
  scale_color_viridis_c(trans=custom_pow) +
  geom_point() + theme_minimal() + labs(x="Workload Time (s)", y="Workload Energy Consumption (PKG)", color="Initial Temperature")

workload_time_model <- glm( delta_seconds ~  initial_temp_1*initial_temp_2+dimension*population_size*evaluations+I(initial_temp_1^2)*I(initial_temp_2^2) , data= initial_workload)
initial_workload$residual_delta_seconds <- residuals(workload_time_model)

initial_workload_model <- glm( delta_PKG ~  initial_temp_1*initial_temp_2+dimension*population_size*evaluations+residual_delta_seconds+I(initial_temp_1^2)*I(initial_temp_2^2) , data= initial_workload)
anova_initial_workload_model <- anova(initial_workload_model, test="F")

sum_F_anova_initial_workload_model <- sum(anova_initial_workload_model$F[2:nrow(anova_initial_workload_model)])

variance_anova_initial_workload <- 100*(anova_initial_workload_model$F[2]+
                                          anova_initial_workload_model$F[3]+
                                          anova_initial_workload_model$F[7]+
                                          anova_initial_workload_model$F[8]+
                                          anova_initial_workload_model$F[9]+
                                          anova_initial_workload_model$F[10]+
                                          anova_initial_workload_model$F[14]
    )/sum_F_anova_initial_workload_model

variance_anova_T_initial_workload <- 100*(anova_initial_workload_model$F[2]+anova_initial_workload_model$F[3]+anova_initial_workload_model$F[8]+anova_initial_workload_model$F[9]+anova_initial_workload_model$F[10]+
                                          anova_initial_workload_model$F[14])/sum_F_anova_initial_workload_model

variance_explained_system_percent_workload <- round(variance_anova_initial_workload, 2)
variance_explained_T_system_percent_workload <- round(variance_anova_T_initial_workload, 2)
@

We process experimental workload data by subtracting $(B_n + B_{n+1})/2$ from every $W_n$ run. This would be the actual energy (Delta or $\Delta$ E) spent by the workload, that is, our algorithm, eliminating (to a certain extent) system and framework overhead. We do the same for the time spent by these runs. The result is plotted in Figure \ref{fig:icsme.baseline.workload}, again using color to represent average initial temperature for the two dies. We perform again the model in two phases: first, we model $\Delta R$ as a function of the other parameters, extract the residual $\Delta R$ unexplained by the model, and use it to model $\Delta E$. This model shows significant coefficients for the operating conditions, as above, and is also significantly dependent on problem size $D$. However, it is not significant on the number of evaluations, thus being unable to distinguish two variations of the algorithm that differ only in that area. The variance explained by the system is around \Sexpr{variance_explained_system_percent_workload}\%, of which \Sexpr{variance_explained_T_system_percent_workload}\% is explained by the temperature terms. What we will need is a way of giving some {\em breathing room} to algorithm parameters by creating an experimental protocol that is able to reduce dependence on operating conditions.

<<icsme.hot, echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=F, fig.cap="Workload delta E vs. delta R, colorized by average initial temperature for the {\\protect\\em hot-first strategy}.", fig.height=3 >>=
load("data/icsm_hot_first.rds")
source("R/process_deltas.R")
library(dplyr)
icsme_hot_workload <- process_deltas(icsm_hot_first)
icsme_hot_workload$dimension <- as.factor(icsme_hot_workload$dimension)
icsme_hot_workload$population_size <- as.factor(icsme_hot_workload$population_size)

hot_workload_time_model <- glm( delta_seconds ~  initial_temp_1*initial_temp_2+dimension*population_size*evaluations+I(initial_temp_1^2)*I(initial_temp_2^2) , data= icsme_hot_workload)
icsme_hot_workload$residual_delta_seconds <- residuals(hot_workload_time_model)

icsme_hot_workload_model <- glm( delta_PKG ~  initial_temp_1*initial_temp_2+dimension*population_size*evaluations+residual_delta_seconds+I(initial_temp_1^2)*I(initial_temp_2^2) , data= icsme_hot_workload)
anova_initial_workload_model <- anova(initial_workload_model, test="F")

ggplot(icsme_hot_workload, aes(x=delta_seconds,y=delta_PKG, color=initial_temp)) +
  scale_color_viridis_c(trans=custom_pow) +
  geom_point() + theme_minimal() + labs(x="Workload Time (s)", y="Workload Energy Consumption (PKG)", color="Initial Temperature")

anova_icsme_hot_workload_model <- anova(icsme_hot_workload_model)
sum_F_anova_icsme_hot_workload_model <- sum(anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[2:nrow(anova_icsme_hot_workload_model)])

variance_anova_icsme_hot_workload <- 100*(anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[2]+anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[3]+anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[7]+anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[8]+anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[9]+anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[10]+
                                          anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[14])/sum_F_anova_icsme_hot_workload_model

variance_anova_T_icsme_hot_workload <- 100*(anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[2]+anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[3]+anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[8]+anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[9]+anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[10]+
                                          anova_icsme_hot_workload_model$F[14])/sum_F_anova_icsme_hot_workload_model

variance_hot_explained_system_percent_workload <- round(variance_anova_icsme_hot_workload, 2)
variance_hot_T_explained_system_percent_workload <- round( variance_anova_T_icsme_hot_workload, 2)
@
%

So what we propose and are going to evaluate in this paper is to use a {\em run-to-idle} strategy. Using the same {\em sandwich} strategy we proposed above, we will set up the running script so that the next process is always run in the die that has the highest temperature using {\sf taskset}. This {\em run-to-idle} strategy is based on the negative quadratic terms of the model above that show that when the temperature is higher, energy consumption decreases thanks to the different mechanisms the system has to keep the temperature within certain bounds, that often include running the process in the most energy-efficient core within the die. After processing data to extract $E_w$ and averaging the temperature for the two dies, we plot $\Delta E$ vs $\Delta R$ in Figure \ref{fig:icsme.hot}. We can observe differences with respect to \ref{fig:icsme.baseline.workload}: the range is smaller, there are very few less-than-zero workload energy data points, meaning that this strategy decreases the probability of big shifts in operating conditions from one run to the next, and overall energy consumption is less spread and also generally less. It is interesting to note that our system under study is the same in both cases: it is the experimental protocol what has achieved these changes.

We create again the two-stage model that includes operating conditions and algorithm parameters, resulting in a model where the number of fitness evaluations in the population-based algorithm is significant at the 90\% level; this implies that, if a different implementation or parametrization of the algorithm results in a different number of evaluations, the model will be able to tell us by how much every individual evaluation will contribute to energy consumption (at the level of confidence indicated, of course). With this new protocol, the variance explained by operating conditions amounts to \Sexpr{variance_hot_explained_system_percent_workload}\% of which \Sexpr{variance_hot_T_explained_system_percent_workload}\% is related to temperature. The difference is relatively small indeed, and the variance explained by temperature has increased. Did we gain anything with the new protocol?

<<icsme.hot.combined, echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=F, fig.cap="Density plot comparing temperature of the second die for the baseline and hot-first strategy">>=
icsme_hot_workload$work <- "hot-first"
initial_workload$work <- "baseline"

icsme_combined <- rbind(icsme_hot_workload,initial_workload)
combined_workload_time_model <- glm( delta_seconds ~  work*initial_temp_1*initial_temp_2+dimension*population_size*evaluations+I(initial_temp_1^2)*I(initial_temp_2^2) , data= icsme_combined)
anova_combined_workload_time_model <- anova(combined_workload_time_model)
icsme_combined$residual_delta_seconds <- residuals(combined_workload_time_model)

icsme_combined_temp_1_model <- glm( initial_temp_1 ~ work, data=icsme_combined)
icsme_combined_temp_2_model <- glm( initial_temp_2 ~ work, data=icsme_combined)

icsme_combined_workload_model <- glm( delta_PKG ~  work*initial_temp_1*initial_temp_2+dimension*population_size*evaluations+residual_delta_seconds+I(initial_temp_1^2)*I(initial_temp_2^2) , data= icsme_combined)

anova_combined_workload_model <- anova( icsme_combined_workload_model )

ggplot(icsme_combined, aes(x = initial_temp_1, fill = work)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.6) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("baseline" = "#E69F00", "hot-first" = "#56B4E9")) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(initial_temp_2[work == "baseline"])),
             color = "#E69F00", linetype = "dashed", size = 1) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(initial_temp_2[work == "hot-first"])),
             color = "#56B4E9", linetype = "dashed", size = 1) +
  labs(
    title = "Thermal Impact: Hot-First Strategy significantly lowers T2",
    subtitle = "Dashed lines represent the mean temperature for each strategy",
    x = "Initial Temperature 1 (°C)",
    y = "Density",
    fill = "Strategy"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

# library(ggExtra)
#
# comparison_gg <- ggplot(icsme_combined, aes(x=initial_temp_1,y=delta_seconds,color=work))+geom_point(alpha=0.5)+theme_minimal() +
#   theme(legend.position = "bottom")
# ggMarginal(comparison_gg, type="density", groupFill=T, alpha=0.5)
#

icsme_hot_model_coefficients <- data.frame(
                                            coefficients=c(coef(icsme_combined_workload_model)['workhot-first'],
                                                            coef(icsme_combined_workload_model)['workhot-first:initial_temp_1'],
                                                            coef(icsme_combined_workload_model)['workhot-first:initial_temp_2'],
                                                            coef(icsme_combined_workload_model)['workhot-first:initial_temp_1:initial_temp_2']
                                                    )
                                            )

library(kableExtra)
icsme_hot_model_coefficients %>%
  kable( caption = "hot-first coefficients in the energy generalized linear model")


@

In order to answer that question we create a combined dataset that includes the initial ("baseline") and hot-first ("hot-first") workload data, and include in the model a variable that represents the dataset. In the two-stage model, we already observe that the dependence of $\Delta R$ on {\sf hot-first} is significant; however, the main coefficient is positive, with negative terms on the interaction between {\sf hot-first} and the two die temperatures, and positive again on the product of the two temperatures; this draws a complex scenario that can be summarized on the new experiments taking more time if $T_1$ is more than around 44º. Although the direction of energy consumption might go against our initial assumption since time has a strong influence on energy consumption, what this certifies is that this new protocol has effectively changed how the experiments behave in one of the components, running time.

Once the $\Delta R$ residuals are extracted and used for model of workload energy consumption depending on system and algorithm variables, we find the coefficients shown in Table \ref{tab:icsme.hot.combined}, all of them significant. Again, this draws a complex scenario; although apparently the net contribution to energy consumption would be positive, for the range of temperatures that is actually experimented there is a zone where the {\sf hot-first} would, effectively, lower the energy consumption. We see, however, that the coefficients for $T_2$ have a higher value than the ones for the temperature of the first die; this is why we make a density plot in Figure \ref{fig:icsme.hot.combined} showing how the temperatures for the two sets of experiments are distributed. What we see is that {\sf hot-first} has a single peak, placed at a lower temperature than the baseline experiments. The new strategy presented in this paper significantly lowers the temperature of the second die.

<<icsme.hot.combined.chart, echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=F, fig.cap="Density plot comparing energy consumption for the baseline and hot-first strategy">>=
library(ggExtra)

ggplot(icsme_combined, aes(x = delta_seconds, y = delta_PKG, fill = work)) +
  # Map alpha to the calculated density level
  stat_density_2d(aes(alpha = after_stat(level)),
                  geom = "polygon",
                  color = "white", # Adds a faint white line between depth levels
                  linewidth = 0.2) +
  # Control the transparency range (0.1 = outer edges, 0.8 = dense center)
  scale_alpha_continuous(range = c(0.1, 0.8), guide = "none") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  labs(
    title = "Execution Time vs Energy (Shaded Depth)",
    x = "Execution Time (delta_seconds)",
    y = "Energy Consumption (delta_PKG)"
  )

