@

We can see the effect on energy consumption in Figure \ref{fig:icsme.hot.combined.chart}, which plots execution time vs. energy consumption. Without the {\sf hot-first} strategy, there are two different {\em regimes} in the operating conditions, leading to a peak with (as we have seen in the previous figure) higher temperature in the second die, longer execution time resulting in more energy consumption; this peak is around 170J and 2.5 seconds. The {\sf hot-first} intervention eliminates this peak; even if a priori it will imply longer execution times for a certain temperature according to the model, the overall effect is that energy consumption in this measurement phase is effectively reduced.

This means that this experimental protocol will help us differentiate better between different configurations of our algorithm; although still a considerable part of the energy consumption will be explained by the operating conditions (temperature and power represented by its proxy running time), the fact that temperature and running time are lowered will allow differences due to algorithm configuration to gather more significance and thus be used as actionable decisions by the researcher.

\section{Conclusion and discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

Evolving software towards more energy-thrifty versions requires a sound methodology that is able to differentiate the effects of the software under study from the operating context. What we have introduced here is a temperature-conscious experimental protocol for measuring energy consumption of different algorithm implementation configurations for multi-die CPUs that is able to minimize the influence of the operating context, maximizing the possibility of distinguishing between the energy consumption requirements of these different configurations.

As far as we can tell, this is the first attempt to heuristically model the behavior of a system so that it can be used as the foundation for a measuring protocol and methodology that can be used by software engineers to compare different configurations in order to create more energy-efficient versions of their applications, specifically of the parts that implement algorithms as business logic. Our methodology tries to separate workload measurements from baseline by using a {\em sandwich} protocol that puts a workload run between two baseline runs, so that the operating environment for the workload is as close as possible to the baseline. We conclude that we can leverage the differential of temperature in a two-die package to reduce its influence in a measurement methodology and achieve at the same time lower energy consumption in the measuring phase. This also certifies the need to study models of energy measurements and how different parameters affect energy measurements in this model. In no case a single statistical measure like an average or median can be used to compare two configurations, since in most cases they will behave differently depending on the operating conditions: again, we need to use statistics and be conscious of the operating environment to decide, at the point of running a model, which configuration is better for a specific scenario.

From the fact that in most models running time is an important, or determinant, factor for energy consumption, we can also conclude that micro-optimizations that make the algorithm implementation faster will be the first target. Other parameters such as population size in the case of population-based optimization algorithms, or even parameters that change the number of iterations until algorithm completion will always have an impact, but in most cases they will count as nano-optimizations or fine-tuning of higher-impact changes. By reducing running time due to operating conditions, this experimental protocol will also help in evaluating these changes with more precision.

% We will not claim that this conclusion is generarizable to all possible processors of all possible brands and all possible operating systems. But, by having these measurements made in a small workload, we do claim that a protocol that tries to put workload and baseline in operating conditions that are as close as possible, as well as a sound, repeated measurement, followed by a modelization of the dependence of energy on operating conditions is a good way to approach the issue of greener algorithm implementations. A methodology should first look to mitigate the impact of operating conditions, and then understand, even so, what affects energy consumption in such a way that it can be optimized under probably operating conditions or under a range of them.

